Project Goals

Primary goals of the project are associated with learning which INPUTS are important!

  • Regression task: Train models to predict the important paint property, response, as a function of the color model INPUTS.

    • Want to learn how the color model INPUTS influence the important paint property!

    • Are the inputs from one color model more influential on predicting the important paint property?

Inputs and Color Models

  • The INPUTS are associated with two alternative color models.

  • The R, G, and B INPUTS are the RGB values from the RGB color model.

  • The Hue, Saturation, and Lightness INPUTS are HSL associated values from the HSL color model.

    • Continuous: R, G, B, Hue

    • Categorical: Lightness, Saturation

Separating red by Lightness appears to make the data more Gaussian in shape, while Saturation gives some Gaussianity and some randomness. The distributions hold relatively well for the binary outcome condition - the shapes appear to be consistently skewed left, but there are much more non-events than events, so we cannot determine if the events is a true skewed left distribution or a random distribution.

Perform logit-transform on response

df_logit <- df %>% 
  mutate(
    y = boot::logit((response - 0) / (100 - 0)) # formula from slide 13 of instruction slides
  )

Visualize logit transformed response with continuous variables

df_logit %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=R, y=y)) +
  geom_point()

There is a moderate correlation between R and y.

df_logit %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=G, y=y)) +
  geom_point()

There is a strong correlation between G and y.

There is a weak correlation between B and y.

Conditioning by Lightness appears to reveal some Gaussianity in each sub-distribution between Hue and y. Saturation still appears to be mostly random.

Overall, there is a tight relationship with gray for R, G and B. The lightness of R, G and B all appear to be clustering close to some value for the given lightness value.
